ombination of bissett and Acorn's seemingly incongruous poetics to confront the turbulent and swiftly changing world of the 1960s. A collection of poems and illustrations, it is a window into the lives and motivations of two soon-to-be-canonized cultural figures. I Want to Tell You Love is a work of friendship, a shared vision of resistance, and a mutual longing for a better world. This critical edition offers the manuscript in its intended form alongside contextualizing scholarship in a significant contribution to literary history. I Want to Tell You Love offers an opportunity to reevaluate the nature and scope of Canadian poetry during a critical time of national cultural awakening.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aPOETRY / Canadian.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aCanadian literature.  aCanadian poetry.  aI shout love.  aI’ve tasted my blood.  aMilton Acorn.  aTISH poets.  aalternative poetry.  abeat generation.  abeat poets, black mountain poets.  abeatniks.  abill bissett, blewointment.  ablu loon producksyun.  aconcrete sound.  acounterculture.  acritical edition.  aexperimental poetry.  afamous Canadian poets.  aliterary history.  alyric poetry.  anineteen sixties.  athe Georgia Straight.  athe people’s poet.  athe sixties.1 aAcorn, Milton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoody, Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchmaltz, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmaltz, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 abissett, bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z9783111272214